zero.

B Existence of a Concave Consumption Function
To show that (6) defines a sequence of continuously differentiable strictly increasing
concave functions {cT , cT âˆ’1 , ..., cT âˆ’k }, we start with a definition. We will say that a
function n(z) is â€˜niceâ€™ if it satisfies
1. n(z) is well-defined iff z > 0
2. n(z) is strictly increasing
3. n(z) is strictly concave
4. n(z) is C3
5. n(z) < 0
6. limzâ†“0 n(z) = âˆ’âˆ.
(Notice that an implication of niceness is that limzâ†“0 n0 (z) = âˆ.)
Assume that some vt+1 is nice. Our objective is to show that this implies vt is also
nice; this is sufficient to establish that vtâˆ’n is nice by induction for all n > 0 because
vT (m) = u(m) and u(m) = m1âˆ’Ï /(1 âˆ’ Ï) is nice by inspection.
